{"key":"processedPost-16132148","value":{"id":16132148,"first":16131182,"last":16135502,"when":1335272292,"utime":"04/24/12 03:58 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>lloydbanks said:</b><br />I will soon be trying to grow wbs spawn to straw using a monotub with 100% verm.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />Straw is a great substrate, but it fruits better uncased, and plain verm is a poor casing layer anyway.<br /> <br /><blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>lloydbanks said:</b>&nbsp; <br />To start: I will be inoculating/spawing using 2 brf cakes into wbs using docs wild bird seed tek.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />You can't do a grain to grain transfer with brf cakes.&nbsp; They are not sterile due to the verm layer on top, and you can't get it off without contaminating the cake outside the jar.&nbsp; You have to start with seed, or learn agar work.&nbsp; You can inject directly into the seed or other grains, but not use a brf cake to inoculate. <br /><br /><blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>lloydbanks said:</b><br />i will colonize 8 quart jars of wbsc at 80 degrees using the aquarium heater method. Once the wbs is fully colonized i will be using straw that is pasteurized using the oven method tek in a 1:4 ratio.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />Colonize jars on an open shelf in a room with normal low-level ambient lighting at normal room temperature.&nbsp; You can't pasteurize in the oven.&nbsp; Use steam or water. Colonize the monotub at normal room temperature too.&nbsp; Be sure to place a weight on the straw to hold it compressed during colonization.<br />RR","title":"Re: WBS to straw monotub with 100% verm casing... first grow questions","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}